I moved from the Mendel90 standard spool holder to this style spool holder because of my heat chamber design didn't give the height needed for the standard design.  I looked at what was out there, and decided I wanted to design my own.  On the top of the box will have strips of 3M Dual Lock on the top of the heat chamber, with pieces of Dual Lock under each end of the spool holders. description.text:
With this update your Z axis will be more precise and you will avoid common problems such as Z waving.
You will need:

  • 2 x SWZ-063009 precision nuts (I bought them here)
  • 2 x threaded rod 8x1.5mm (lenght 360mm) (I bought them here)

You will also need to modify your firmware, it's a simple line in Configuration.h but it's important because the new rods have a different pitch than the original ones. So, go to Configuration.h, comment the first as follows:

//#define DEFAULT_AXIS_STEPS_PER_UNIT {80.19,80.43,2560,458.3} // BCN3D+ default

And add the new line:

#define DEFAULT_AXIS_STEPS_PER_UNIT {80.19,80.43,2117.048,458.3} // BCN3D+ HD (precision Z rods from IGUS with 1.5 thread pitch). Theoretically it should be 2560/1.5 but 2117.048 was fine calibrated and outputs better results, I recommend recalibrate it for your specific printer

Of course you can play around with the config parameters in the SCAD source file and modify them to build your own clamp.

These are top and bottom parts for custom length legs for 3DR IRIS+.
You can use any length of 6 mm diameter aluminium, carbon fiber or wood rod as the leg itself and attach these top and bottom parts.

Use epoxy (or some other glue) on both ends of the rods (actually, my aluminium rods are just pressed into the parts and are plenty tight.)

I'm using an M3 threaded insert (like this one from McMaster-Carr) for holding the locking screw. You can do without if the fit is snug enough (or you can add a piece of tape or something to make the fit snug enough).

Depending on the tolerances of your 3D printer, you might need to drill out the 6 mm hole (and possibly the 4 mm hole for the threaded insert).

With the aluminium tubes, I'm using in the picture, each leg weighs in a 1.5 grams more than the stock long legs.

description.text:
I received a Biopop Dino Sphere as a gift: http://biopop.com/products/dino-sphere

It has a flat bottom and displays fine on its own sitting on a desk/table/shelf/etc., but I wanted something a bit nicer.

The Dino Sphere contains living creatures (bioluminescent marine plankton), so they need to get light throughout the day to survive (photosynthesis!). This lead to a minimalistic design that optimizes light exposure.

The print pictured is the prototype. I intend to reprint at higher settings and do some finishing. Considering a wood filament.

While a very niche print, I hope someone enjoys it!

title: Arrow Tail Fin Joiner (for RC Wings)

description.text:
My buddy Glade created a tail fin joiner from plywood and carbon fiber. We took the design and created a 3D printed part that was much easier to work with and set the angle for the joiner with ease. This was designed and used on the FliteTest Arrow design. It could be scaled up for larger wings.

The tube holes accept 3mm or 1/8th inch carbon tubes. Just glue them in. Put a barbecue skewer under the tail fin and glue it in the slot. The carbon tubes are then fit up into the wing and glued in place.

This is a variable length and ring AR printable form of a chainmaille weave coined Jens Pinds Linkage.
More information on the weave itself can be found here: http://www.mailleartisans.org/weaves/weavedisplay.php?key=335 The math for this one was interesting, as the changing ARs cause the angles to change. It turned into a very interesting parametric geometry problem after identifying that the angle needed to be changed depending on the AR.

Open in customizer to generate your stl file for printing.
Sometimes the customizer does not launch correctly. If this is the case, follow this link: http://www.thingiverse.com/apps/customizer This weave is really difficult to model nicely, so the full AR range may not be functional. Increasing the smoothness value decreases the chance of fusing rings. The AR range that is functional for this script is 2.8-3.1. Smaller ARs are likely to fuse rings together, which could probably be repaired post-printing.

My previous windmill/spinner was nice (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1536061) but... I wanted to print something big and functional on my 8.9" x 5.7" x 5.9" print area printer, so... here it is, a 37" inch diameter yard windmill/spinner. :)

I drew it up so that there is almost no support needed. The only part that requires support is the Mount.

Printed with PETG, since it's my favorite stuff. 6 layers top, bottom, and sides with 20% infill.

You will also need some hardware (I've included a pic) and 3/4" water pipe. Everything is relative to what you have as I designed it to what hardware I had on hand. I used:

6pcs of 4d finish nails
6pcs of 3mmx10mm nylon screws
2pcs 1/4-20x2" bolts
4pcs 1/4" washers
4pcs 1/4-20 nuts
glue
3/4" water pipe (1.05 OD)
